		<description><![CDATA[<img width="210" height="158" src="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Jacob-Zuma-in-Lusikisiki-210x158.jpg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="" style="float: left; margin-right: 5px;" srcset="http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Jacob-Zuma-in-Lusikisiki-210x158.jpg 210w, http://www.newspages.co.za/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Jacob-Zuma-in-Lusikisiki-16x11.jpg 16w" sizes="(max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px" /><p>President Jacob Zuma has taken a task to the community of Lusikisiki and neighbouring areas in the Eastern Cape that government will strengthen the delivery of basic services to the people and also ensure decisive action against crime.</p>
<p>Zuma paid a &#8220;Siyahlola presidential monitoring visit&#8221; to Lusikisiki on Saturday and began his visit by taking a guided tour of the new Lusikisiki police station.</p>
<p>&#8220;We believe that this new police station will make a significant contribution to our fight to reduce crime in this community and defeat the scourge, particularly of gangsterism, in the form of &#8216;Amavondo&#8217;, about which I have received a number of complaints,&#8221; he said.</p>
<p>Zuma then proceeded to the community engagement part of his visit where members of the community expressed their grievances and also provided suggestions.</p>
<p>They said government needed to address the root causes of crime and gangsterism in the area, which were unemployment and the delivery of services. They especially appealed for help to promote investments in factories and industry in the area and also asked for the improvement of the R61 road.</p>
<p>Zuma concluded the programme by undertaking to ensure that all the levels of government he brought to Lusikisiki worked speedily together to address all the challenges of the community.</p>
